          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> <em>Get great reading recommendations delivered to your inbox. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Sign up</a> for the weekly Books newsletter.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 16:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b<category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> opinion </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Lost Bread’ Review: A Child Endures Auschwitz]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Edith Bruck&#39;s evocative novel is rooted in the author&#39;s own experience as a child survivor of the Holocaust. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590079743510237872"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816496?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A group of children at Auschwitz-Birkenau during the liberation of the camp in 1945.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alexander Vorontsov/Galerie Bilderwelt/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590079743510237872"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Diane Cole</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 14, 2023 12:30 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-bread-review-pale-faces-famished-eyes-f234ed44"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The 92-year-old Holocaust survivor Edith Bruck is so celebrated in Italy that Pope Francis not only paid her a visit at her home in Rome in 2021, but also invited her to the Vatican and wrote the preface to “Sono Francesco” (“I Am Francis”), Ms. Bruck&#39;s 2022 book recounting their conversation and their shared belief in the need to remember the past. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/fae4a26b-ca2d-4bb9-b25b-4df6e3b9cdd0.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Ms. Bruck begins “Lost Bread”—as she did her 1959 memoir, “Who Loves You Like This”—by conjuring her own impoverished childhood in a small, close-knit Hungarian village. It is an idyllic place for a young girl, named Ditke—as the young Edith was also called—to dance barefoot in the dusty streets. But soon Ditke&#39;s formerly friendly Christian neighbors conform to the increasingly vicious antisemitic mandates, and the Jewish girl suddenly finds herself in a “world gone back to barbarism.” That is also the new reality that Ms. Bruck, forced into maturity at age 12, confronted when the Nazis deported her and her family to Auschwitz in 1944.</p><p> Originally published in Italian in 2021, “Lost Bread” has been labeled by Ms. Bruck&#39;s publisher as a novel. But the book&#39;s story tracks so closely to the details of its author&#39;s life that it would be more accurately classified as an autobiographical novel infused with occasional flights of fancy, sudden jumps in narrative viewpoint, and almost hallucinatory descriptions of the horrors witnessed in the concentration camps. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817423?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The long journey of modern Spain, the father of species, a history of better worlds and more.</p></div></div><p> Very soon after their arrival at Auschwitz, Ditke is separated from her mother, and the two are sentenced to opposite fates: to the left, the gas chamber; to the right, the workers&#39; barracks, where Ditke cries out incessantly for her mother, stopping only when another inmate points to the billowing smoke of the crematorium and taunts: “She has been burned!”</p><p> For the young Ditke, an oven was a kitchen hearth used to bake the family&#39;s daily bread. But at Auschwitz she comes to view ovens as murderous instruments for turning human bodies into ash. The severely rationed lumps of bread handed to the camp inmates are not meant to sustain them but to slowly starve them in body and soul.</p><p> In an interview conducted by Gabriella Romani, who, together with David Yanoff, capably translated “Lost Bread,” Ms. Bruck has elaborated on the link between bread and life: “At some level I identify my mother with bread. Also, because she used to make bread, she kneaded it, her apron smelled of flour and therefore, for me, she was symbolically my bread. And for her, the most important thing was to provide bread for her children.”</p><p> This symbiosis helps explain Ditke&#39;s mother&#39;s near-delirious lament, as she is herded into a cattle car bound for Auschwitz, for the “lost bread” she has been forced to leave behind. Rather than being burned, however, those loaves had yet even to be placed in the oven. It&#39;s an anguished allusion to the many future generations of Jews never to be born because of the Holocaust.</p><p> After Ditke finds her older sister, Judit, in the Auschwitz barracks, the two are sent from one camp to another, laboring at Dachau until they fall “under the weight of the rail ties” they are forced to carry even as their German guards hound them “to work faster,” laughing at their “haggard faces and famished eyes” while throwing sausages to their dogs. Soon after, the guards order the prisoners on an endless death march to an unknown destination, “seeding the earth with cadavers on the way.”</p><p> After five weeks of marching, Ditke is left so fragile that her sister must drag her “on the frozen roads as if [she] were a sled.” They arrive at Bergen Belsen, where they are greeted by a human pyramid of naked corpses. A few prisoners, barely breathing, murmur “their names and places of origin,” begging those who can hear them to tell the world what they have witnessed.</p><p> This is the pledge Ms. Bruck has sought to fulfill through her writing. But there remained a question: In which language would she—could she—bear to remember? As she roamed through Europe after liberation, she found that, for her, her native Hungarian had become poisoned with the memories of antisemitic slurs.</p><p> The narrator of “Lost Bread” hopes, as Ms. Bruck once did, to find a new life—and a new language—in the newly formed state of Israel. But the “Babelic” tongues of so many immigrants from so many countries provide little consolation. There is also the gulf, in Israel as in Europe, between the Jews who have survived the camps and those who have not—an abyss of understanding, regardless of language.</p><p> Still unmoored, Ditke joins a dance group and arrives, at the end of a European tour, in Italy. There, for the first time, she feels “immediately at home, after such a long, sad pilgrimage.” In the Italian language she discovers the words she needs “to speak about Auschwitz.” Indeed, this is the language in which Ms. Bruck has written more than 20 books of fiction, memoir and poetry; composed film and television scripts; and delivered so many educational talks about the Holocaust that she is known in Italy as Signora Auschwitz.</p><p> Writing in Italian, says Ms. Bruck to Ms. Romani in her interview (which has been appended to the book), has given the author “complete freedom to say what I want.” She uses the example of—what else—bread. “If I say bread in Hungarian, <em>kenyér</em> , I think of my mother, and tragic memories come to my mind. 。 。 。 If I say bread in Italian, <em>pane</em> , I think of the bakery where I buy it, of its fragrance, but nothing else. 。 。 。 It does not make me cry. While bread in Hungarian still hurts.”</p><p> In whatever language you encounter Ms. Bruck&#39;s work, her spare prose captures the raw terror and bitter sorrow of the camps. She also finds lyrical beauty and unexpected joy in moments of calm. Reading her work is like breaking bread with her, seeking light amid the shadows cast by history.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ms. Cole is the author of the memoir “After Great Pain: A New Life Emerges.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 16:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-bread-review-pale-faces-famished-eyes-f234ed44</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lost-bread-review-pale-faces-famished-eyes-f234ed44<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews</category><category> opinion </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Spain’ Review: After Franco, Renewal]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A country long beset by violent division and dictatorial rule has somehow created a boisterous liberal democracy. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082222255583364"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816490?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Gen. Francisco Franco in Seville, Spain, in 1967.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dominique Berretty/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590082222255583364"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Tunku Varadarajan</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 14, 2023 11:31 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-review-after-franco-renewal-77349183"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In 1971, four years before the death of Francisco Franco, President Richard Nixon sent a high-level envoy to Madrid to suss out what might happen to Spain after its long-lived dictator was gone. It was a subject, the envoy found, that nobody dared discuss—except for the generalissimo himself, who asked his American interlocutor to tell Nixon that Spain would be just fine. The Spanish middle class—which Franco believed was his most important legacy—would ensure, he said, that “there won&#39;t be another civil war.” He even predicted that there&#39;d be “democracy” in Spain—along with “pornography, drugs and so forth.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/2c4e50b1-6c90-4d5c-9bd2-ccd1b39ba936.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> This comment was, writes Michael Reid, “surprisingly perspicacious” of the old despot. The civic wisdom of the <em>burguesía</em> —the Spanish bourgeoisie—gave rise to a “largely seamless transition” from a paternalistic Catholic dictatorship (which had lasted from 1939 to 1975) to a modern, liberal democracy, one that matches Scandinavia for its personal freedoms and surpasses any other in Europe in the granting of wide-ranging autonomy to its regions.</p><p> As Mr. Reid reminds us in “Spain: The Trials and Triumphs of a Modern European Country,” Spain&#39;s post-Franco democracy was “not imposed by conquering foreign armies, as in Germany or Italy” after World War II. Rather it was the homegrown fruit of Spain&#39;s own common sense, nurtured through agreements between “moderate supporters of the dictatorship and a realistic democratic opposition.” The aplomb with which Spaniards—who you&#39;d think would be locked into uncompromising hatreds after 36 years of Franco—overcame their distaste for those with whom they disagreed suggests that Spain may well be the most impressively democratic major country in mainland Europe. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b" target="_blank" class="icon none">15 Books We Read This Week</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-68144b1b"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817423?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p> The long journey of modern Spain, the father of species, a history of better worlds and more.</p></div></div><p> That doesn&#39;t mean that Spain&#39;s democracy isn&#39;t messy. Its general elections on July 23 will be the fifth since 2015, too many by any yardstick. But as the US, Britain and Germany drift along under rudderless leaders and France burns under an arrogant one, it&#39;s clear that Spain&#39;s politics are no more unkempt than the present Western norm. Spain&#39;s failings are attributable to the same factors that beset all the others, including (writes Mr. Reid) “hubris, austerity, populism, polarisation” and the struggle to keep up with the economic and demographic effects of globalization and technological change.</p><p> Mr. Reid, a British journalist, is a veteran reporter and commentator on Spain and Latin America. He lives in Madrid, where he was the correspondent for the Economist from 2016 to 2021, turbulent years in Spanish politics that saw the collapse of a de facto two-party system and the riotous emergence of smaller parties on the far left and the nationalist right that have made absolute majorities near-impossible in Parliament. Spain is now a country where governments need to be formed by coalition, yet few polities are as little inclined to coalesce.</p><p> The last elections, in November 2019, saw the first coalition government in Spain since the 1930s. In a rickety but tenacious compact, the Socialists under Prime Minister Pedro Sánchez aligned with the communist-lite Podemos party, with the support of Catalan and Basque separatists. More than any other Western country, Spain faces the demon of separatism, in particular in Catalonia, a prosperous territory that seems locked in a spiral of permanent (and, to the outsider, inexplicable) political disaffection. Mr. Reid quotes the Spanish philosopher José Ortega y Gasset, who argued in 1932 that Catalonia was a problem that “cannot be settled, it can only be lived with.”</p><p> While it can&#39;t be denied that the Catalans (and the Basques) were treated harshly by Franco, the democratic constitution of 1978 bestowed on the country&#39;s regions a lavish degree of self-government, which has been constantly enhanced in response to ceaseless Catalan demands. It is gratifying to see Mr. Reid pierce through the separatist cant: One of the most “bizarre” things he encountered while covering this question, he says, was to hear Catalan officials solemnly compare their “prosperous, sophisticated” region to war-torn Kosovo. “It was hard to keep a straight face.”</p><p> The dust jacket of the book carries a blurb from Antonio Muñoz Molina, a renowned Spanish novelist, who describes Mr. Reid&#39;s effort as “the best and most complete book I have read about Spain today.” Such endorsements are usually overblown, but the praise, in this case, is not misplaced. Spain&#39;s politics and—in particular—its history can be head-spinningly complex; but Mr. Reid has a gift for making the abstruse accessible, and he maintains a superb narrative evenhandedness that is invaluable in any account of a society as ideologically riven as Spain&#39;s.</p><p> He is particularly good on Spain&#39;s transition to democracy in the late 1970s, accomplished by moderates in the Franco regime “who knew that social peace and integration into Europe required democracy” and an opposition “rendered pragmatic” by exile, prison or self-censorship under Franco. The left, which had fought the Spanish Civil War to attain a republic, accepted a parliamentary monarchy; and the right suppressed its wish for a unitary state and embraced sweeping constitutional prerogatives for the regions. An amnesty guaranteed that no Francoist officials would be prosecuted for actions taken during the dictatorship.</p><p> Mr. Reid argues—and few could disagree—that Spain&#39;s transition to democracy was successful precisely because it didn&#39;t incorporate retributive justice, which would have degenerated into witch hunts. He is also correct to point out that the conventional narrative of the civil war as a “heroic anti-fascist struggle”—largely the construct of the many foreigners who wrote Spain&#39;s history while Franco was alive—tends to flatten the complexities of a war in which “red terror” was also a feature.</p><p> Mr. Reid is right to acknowledge that modern Spain is not—and has never been—“in thrall to Franco&#39;s ghost.” In the first decades of democracy, in fact, Spanish nationalism was in “abeyance, discredited by the authoritarian form it had taken under Franco.” Spain&#39;s national anthem, for instance, has been performed without words since 1978, when its Franco-era lyrics were dumped. Yet the separatist incontinence in Catalonia has resulted in a backlash, with the emergence of Vox, a right-wing populist party that seeks a somewhat incoherent, but nonetheless resonant and unabashed, vindication of Spanishness. This includes everything from a defense of bullfighting—a tradition under siege by the politically correct—to a curbing of illegal immigration and a putting in their place of pesky Catalans.</p><p> Vox could well be in a coalition government later this month if, as expected, the conservative Popular Party wins a plurality but falls short of a majority in Parliament. Vox&#39;s leaders make no reference to Franco in their campaigning, instead identifying themselves most closely—Mr. Reid explains—with the aims and credo of the Catholic nationalist government in Poland. But the party&#39;s emergence, along with the possibility of its entry into government, has given scaremongers on the left the chance to raise the specter of Franco. Be very afraid, they tell Spanish voters, women in particular. As it goes to the polls next Sunday, Spain will need to rely, once more, on the common sense of the middle class in which Franco had such bracing faith.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Varadarajan, a Journal contributor, is a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute and at Columbia University&#39;s Center on Capitalism and Society.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 15:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-review-after-franco-renewal-77349183</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-review-after-franco-renewal-77349183<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category> Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews</category><category> opinion</category></item></channel></rss>